WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.760
Hi, my name is Mina Çetinkaya-Rundel and I am a developer educator at Posit as well

00:00:08.760 --> 00:00:14.160
as a professor of the practice at Duke University. And in this video, I'd like to introduce you

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:18.440
to Quarto. So if you've been hearing a lot about Quarto and wanting to dive in and sort

00:00:18.440 --> 00:00:22.920
of have been waiting to see when is the right time for me, or if you've played with it a

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:28.280
little bit and want to get a sense of what more it can do and what more you can do with

00:00:28.280 --> 00:00:34.320
it, hopefully this will be a good introduction for you. So we are going to start things pretty

00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:40.900
simply. We're going to start with a single Quarto document. I am going to open that up

00:00:40.900 --> 00:00:47.720
in RStudio. So let's go ahead and open that up. My Quarto document is called index.qmd.

00:00:47.720 --> 00:00:54.160
For those of you who are familiar with R Markdown, you're probably familiar with file suffixes

00:00:54.160 --> 00:01:00.240
called RMD and Quarto documents are called QMD. At the top of this document, things should

00:01:00.240 --> 00:01:06.800
look pretty familiar. We have a YAML with some metadata about our document, a title,

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:12.120
the format that we want to output to. So we're going to make an HTML document first, and

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:18.000
I'm going to use the RStudio visual editor. So again, if you are familiar with R Markdown

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:23.379
and haven't played with RStudio visual editor lately, you can switch over to the source

00:01:23.379 --> 00:01:29.540
editor and things should look pretty familiar to you. But let's go back to the visual editor

00:01:29.540 --> 00:01:35.699
where you get a document that feels a bit more like Google Docs or writing in an app

00:01:35.699 --> 00:01:41.059
like Notion where things are a little bit more what you see is what you get. For example,

00:01:41.059 --> 00:01:45.860
I have some information about the dataset I'm going to use here, the penguins dataset

00:01:45.860 --> 00:01:50.980
from the Palmer penguins package, and I might want to bold the name of the package and I

00:01:50.980 --> 00:01:58.260
can do that by using the toolbar here, or I can use keyboard shortcuts to do that as

00:01:58.260 --> 00:02:03.739
well. The visual editor has other handy tools on the toolbar. For example, I can directly

00:02:03.739 --> 00:02:14.020
add a link to this. So let's go ahead and add a link to the Palmer penguins website

00:02:14.020 --> 00:02:20.860
and hit OK. So that now is a live link. And if we were to switch over back to the source

00:02:20.860 --> 00:02:26.259
editor, if you are familiar with writing things in Markdown, you can see that under the hood,

00:02:26.259 --> 00:02:30.539
it is writing the Markdown for you. It's just that you are not the one having to write the

00:02:30.539 --> 00:02:36.899
Markdown. So let's go ahead and render this document and let's see what it looks like.

00:02:36.899 --> 00:02:46.059
A setting that I like to use on my RStudio IDE is I generally like to preview my documents

00:02:46.059 --> 00:02:51.380
in the viewer pane so that I can see my source code on one side and my rendered document

00:02:51.380 --> 00:02:56.500
on the other side. So we should be able to see our rendered documents here in the viewer

00:02:56.500 --> 00:03:02.500
pane on the right hand side of our RStudio IDE. Things will look pretty similar between

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:09.580
the source document and the rendered document because our source document is also using

00:03:09.580 --> 00:03:15.220
this visual format. But the difference is that on the source side, we only have the

00:03:15.220 --> 00:03:22.580
code and on the output side, we're seeing the code and the output to go along with it.

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:28.220
So let's introduce you to a few of Porto's features now. We can see that we are taking

00:03:28.220 --> 00:03:35.100
a look at the Palmer Penguins dataset and we have a visualization here for it, but we

00:03:35.100 --> 00:03:40.339
might want to take a look at the actual data itself. So I am going to go ahead and insert

00:03:40.339 --> 00:03:48.460
a code chunk here, which I can do either with the insert code chunk menu here, or using

00:03:48.460 --> 00:03:54.779
my keyboard shortcut with the forward slash and bringing up the insert to anything toolbar.

00:03:55.339 --> 00:04:04.820
I'll say I want an art code chunk. Let's say that I want to glimpse at the Penguins dataset.

00:04:04.820 --> 00:04:10.419
Let's go ahead and render that document and we'll be able to see the input and the output

00:04:10.419 --> 00:04:18.579
on the viewer side. Scrolling down on this document, I have a code chunk that generates

00:04:18.579 --> 00:04:26.459
a plot. So one thing that I might want to do is add an alternative text to this figure,

00:04:26.459 --> 00:04:33.579
for example, and I can do that by using the fake out chunk option. The visual editor nicely

00:04:33.579 --> 00:04:39.700
does YAML completion for me, so I can choose from here which chunk option I want to use.

00:04:39.700 --> 00:04:45.459
I'm going to go with fake out and I have a multi-line chunk option. So I'm going to use

00:04:45.459 --> 00:04:50.339
this vertical bar here. I've already written the out text, so I will just copy and paste

00:04:50.339 --> 00:04:54.500
that here. So you don't have to watch me type this out, but basically we're saying that

00:04:54.500 --> 00:04:59.859
this is a scatter plot of Penguins build depth and length, colored by species. And we say

00:04:59.859 --> 00:05:05.140
something about the trend we see. It's relatively strong and a linear association. Let's go

00:05:05.140 --> 00:05:09.859
ahead and render this document. And when we render the document, the alternative text

00:05:09.859 --> 00:05:15.019
won't show on the output because again, it's not part of the output necessarily, but the

00:05:15.019 --> 00:05:22.459
underlying source code. But if I pop this out to a browser window and scroll down to

00:05:22.459 --> 00:05:31.820
my figure and right click on it to inspect it, I should be able to see that the out text

00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:38.700
is actually available for me under the hood. If I'm writing a report, I might want to not

00:05:38.700 --> 00:05:45.660
necessarily show all of this code on the output. So one thing I can do is I can hide

00:05:45.660 --> 00:05:54.619
the code one chunk at a time with another chunk option, eco false. And that will only

00:05:54.619 --> 00:06:01.420
hide that particular chunk option, that particular code chunks code. But if I want to do that

00:06:01.420 --> 00:06:08.059
at the document level, I have a few options as well. I can actually go to the YAML on

00:06:08.059 --> 00:06:16.859
top of my document and under execute, say I want to do eco false. And let's go ahead

00:06:16.859 --> 00:06:22.220
and render this full document. And we will see that all of the code is now hidden and

00:06:22.220 --> 00:06:27.420
we only have the output, which might be preferable for you depending on your audience, whether

00:06:27.420 --> 00:06:34.940
you want them to see the code or not. And here we go. Here's our output without any of the code.

00:06:35.899 --> 00:06:42.140
Over here, we have a figure that's being generated with code. And in the text, I have said the

00:06:42.140 --> 00:06:48.380
figure below is a bar is actually a scatterplot. Let's go ahead and pull up that scatterplot

00:06:48.380 --> 00:06:55.579
of species of penguins. We can add cross references to this. So in order to add a cross reference,

00:06:55.579 --> 00:07:02.140
I need to do two things. First, I need to change my chunk label to include the word

00:07:02.380 --> 00:07:11.179
fig at the beginning as a suffix. So that's fig dash. And second, I need to add a caption. So

00:07:11.179 --> 00:07:20.459
to add a caption, I will use the fig cap. And maybe let's go ahead and reuse this information

00:07:20.459 --> 00:07:34.700
from here. All right, so now I have a figure that has a label that starts with fig and a caption.

00:07:35.500 --> 00:07:40.459
All right, so let's highlight this. And let's say we want to insert a cross reference.

00:07:42.779 --> 00:07:48.299
The figure is available for me to choose here. And if I render the document one more time,

00:07:48.299 --> 00:07:53.339
it will create a link to the figure itself. So now I don't need to worry about when I render

00:07:53.339 --> 00:07:58.779
my document if it's below or above, particularly if I'm outputting to something like PDF.

00:07:58.779 --> 00:08:05.019
I can do the same thing with tables as well. The only difference is that I would need to add the

00:08:05.019 --> 00:08:14.140
TBL for table suffix. And similarly, I need to add a caption for that too. So this will be,

00:08:14.779 --> 00:08:18.220
um, let's say the first 10 penguins.

00:08:21.179 --> 00:08:27.420
And let's go ahead and do this without using the insert menu. I can simply grab the label

00:08:27.980 --> 00:08:35.500
and I can say instead of the table below at and the name of my table, and I can render my document

00:08:35.500 --> 00:08:40.940
and it will do the counting and the labeling of my figures for figures and tables for me.

00:08:40.940 --> 00:08:46.059
So I have a figure one here, um, and then a table that's going to be cross-referenced

00:08:46.059 --> 00:08:55.099
underneath it as well. And here we go. We also have a table one. The last thing I'd like to

00:08:55.099 --> 00:09:00.940
show in the visual editor is adding citations, which can be a huge hassle sometimes. So here

00:09:01.580 --> 00:09:06.940
we are going to cite where these data come from. So in order to do that, I'm going to say,

00:09:06.940 --> 00:09:12.780
I want to insert a citation and you can see that I have some options to choose from in terms of

00:09:12.780 --> 00:09:20.299
where my citations can come, but I am going to go ahead and grab the DOI of the paper where

00:09:20.299 --> 00:09:28.299
the Palmer penguins data were originally published. And I can say that I want to insert this. Um,

00:09:29.179 --> 00:09:35.500
and when I do so two things happen, uh, reference gets added, gets added here.

00:09:35.500 --> 00:09:41.739
And you can see that my YAML already also gained a new line called bibliography.

00:09:41.739 --> 00:09:48.299
And if I go to my files, I have actually gained a file called references.bib. And in this file

00:09:48.859 --> 00:09:55.659
is the sort of the bib reference for this paper. So if we go ahead and render this document,

00:09:56.460 --> 00:10:02.380
we will see that the reference has been added. If I hover over it, I can see it. Or if I click

00:10:02.380 --> 00:10:07.979
on it, it will take me to the end of my document where I have a section called references inserted

00:10:07.979 --> 00:10:15.659
for me. So we've talked about creating a single document with Porto. Um, and this has been a HTML

00:10:15.659 --> 00:10:22.460
document so far. If I want to change the output to something like a PDF, all I need to do is

00:10:22.780 --> 00:10:27.099
indicate that on my YAML. So let's go ahead and give that a render too.

00:10:29.580 --> 00:10:35.820
I don't need to change anything in terms of the syntax in my document, right? Now we have

00:10:35.820 --> 00:10:43.020
a PDF document with the same content also hiding the code. Um, so respecting the YAML options that

00:10:43.020 --> 00:10:50.460
we had, um, indicated earlier. And the nice thing about this PDF document is not only, um, did I,

00:10:50.460 --> 00:10:55.739
was I able to obtain it so easily, but it also shows up in my viewer tab as opposed to a pop-up

00:10:55.739 --> 00:11:02.380
window. Now let's go ahead and change things up even more. We've gone from a single HTML document

00:11:02.380 --> 00:11:08.460
to a single PDF document. What about making slides? So I'm going to make HTML based slides

